Aside from the apparent fact that Russia has no particular incentive at the present time to release Griner, President Putin has - in past instances - generally adhered to the established process for the granting of pardons which first requires consideration by the Presidential Pardons Commission of the Federation. The commission has opened up no case involving Griner so it's unlikely that, even if one were opened immediately, it would be resolved by 8 November. Of course, he is not bound to adhere to this process or, in fact, even issue a pardon (he could simply deport her).

To better understand the case of Brittney Griner's captivity, I've looked at cases in which a US national was detained by either the present-day Russian Federation or the former Soviet Union. Between the 1930s and the 1950s periods of detention tended to be longer, spanning as much as two decades. from the 1960s to 1980s, we see only two cases of detentions, lasting only one and three years respectively. Skipping ahead to the more recent detentions of Trevor Reed, we see that he was released after four years. There does not appear to be any relationship between prisoners' USG affiliation and the length of their detention. However, the length of detention appears to have trended downward over time. Two other US nationals--Paul Whelan (four years) and Marc Fol (one year)--are being held by Russian authorities concurrently with Ms. Griner. Based on the length of the most recent historic detentions, I would say that Russian authorities tend to hold Americans for one to four years. Ms. Griner is near the low end of that range, so I don't think it is likely (5% chance) that she will be released before 8 November 2022.

The date on this question makes it a midterms question. That shifts the question to "do democrats want this as a key issue or accomplishment heading in to the elections?" I don't think it is likely that they will want the view from the public that they will negotiate with Russia, especially with the ongoing war. Also, from things I have seen, they people that are being rumored to be offered in return are Russian arms dealers. So I just don't think it is a good look going into an election to be negotiating giving away a terrorist in return for a WNBA star.

Prisoner swaps take a lot of time, especially between 2 countries that absolutely hate eachother. Normally, there would be updates on how negotiations are proceeding or a plan for bringing the prisoner home. However, the US government has been very quiet recently, which tells me that negotiations aren't proceeding well. The US is reluctant to give up more than one prisoner, especially a high profile arms dealer Viktor Bout (Merchant of Death). Everything about the situation tells me that both sides can't reach an agreement and it will likely take much, much longer than a month and a half to reach a proper deal. There is a chance the war in Ukraine ends and perhaps Griner comes back quietly after the war, but the chances of that are very unlikely. Griner will come back eventually, but the problem is the time limit in this case.

It either will or will not happen, so for an initial forecast, I'm starting with a baseline of 50% prior probability. As this is a relatively high profile case, I believe there is an heightened incentive to get a deal done. However, the proxy war between the West and Russia, executed primarily by Ukrainian forces on Ukrainian territory confounds the issue as Russia has very few bargaining chips to hold the US to the table diplomatically. With a progressive US regime, I believe it is unlikely that they will allow a high-profile (for a variety of reasons) entity to remain imprisoned by Russia for a significant period. Regardless of care for its citizens, I believe that social pressure will push the US to make a deal to get Griner freed. However, I do not strongly believe that it will happen based on the Mid-term election (8 Nov) timeline, so that lowers my probability. My probability would be higher if the time horizon was by 1 January 2023 or beyond.

Previous releases of "hostages" such as Trevor Reed took years to happen. Paul Whelan is already in Russian custody since 2018. Griner is such a public figure and a civilian, making this a high value detainee. Releasing her before US midterms would hand Democrats a win, which are more inconvenient to Putin than Republicans. Also due to war in Ukraine, Russia will want significant concessions and I think US might not be ready to give them up yet. All in all, this looks like against a speedy resolution of the problem.

Coming way down after reading more details and thinking a bit more. The US has proposed a two-for-one deal, but the Russians want one-for-one and, in particular, their assassin, in exchange, presumably, for our "spy" (Whelan was convicted of espionage in Russia). Had the US asked only for Griner in exchange for Bout, I would stay at (0.95). Had the US offered (and could deliver) Krasikov for Whelan in addition to Griner for Bout, I might go higher (0.99). Krasikov appears to be high value.

Despite the current conflict, both countries want to negotiate for the release of their citizens. In addition, I believe that a certain level of diplomatic relations between the two countries has to exist for such an outcome.

I may regret even playing this one, but I'm going to go with zero chance. Brittney is a very low value prisoner and hasn't been there long enough compared to others we would like to bring home. Russia will make us squirm longer.

The Ukraine war has little to nothing do with the possibility of Griner being released before 8 Nov 22, which is Election Day in US. It's also unlikely to help the Dems, or her friends and family. In the "spy trade" bidness, Brittney Griner has no value. The man called Victor Bout has a lot. But balance that value with possibility that some influencers in the Russian intelligence establishment and a few Lubyanka old timers were never very pleased with Bout's freelancer style and are more than happy to see Uncle Sam continue to pick up the bill. Another possibility she will not leave before the date mentioned is that some in the Russian sports establishment would like to see how she responds physically and mentally to the living in a tough "Camp" environment. Griner fans don't have the "handgeld" that Ghislaine Maxwell's family does so it is more difficult for her crowd to pay a lawyer in Russian Federation to arrange for her to live in a "country club" jail.
